Community detection using Louvain algorithm¶

What is the Louvain community detection model?¶

The Louvain algorithm is a greedy optimization method that attempts to optimize the "modularity" of a partition of the network (for more details: https://perso.uclouvain.be/vincent.blondel/research/louvain.html). The idea behing the concept of modularity is that a community is a sub-graph which is not random and modularity is a metric that measures how far a partition is compared to a random graph. The optimisation model will try to find the partition which maximizes modularity (for more details regarding the mathematical formula of modularity, check out https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modularity_%28networks%29)

We will use the Louvain model to group products which are similar to one another from the product_proximity.txt file.

Product proximity data set description¶

The dataset product_proximity.txt contains data on a set of products and a proximity measure that measures how close two products are (based on correlation of exports---but it is not so important how this was derived). The first two columns represent the node numbers (representing the products) and the third column, the weight (the proximity) of the nodes.

Graph the "product network"¶

In the graph below, the size of the node depends on the number of inward edges (edges coming from another product) and the size of the edge depends on the proximity measure assigned (or weights) between the two products.

In [2]:
G0 = nx.read_edgelist("./" + "product_proximity.txt", nodetype=int, data=(('weight',float),), create_using=nx.DiGraph()  )

G1 = G0.copy()

#pos = nx.spring_layout(G0, seed=1)
pos = nx.circular_layout(G1)

plt.axis('off')
plt.title("Product Proximity", fontsize=16)
plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

#Filter values in terms of proximity: 
high_values = [(u,v) for (u,v,d) in G0.edges(data=True) if d['weight']>=0.5]
for x in G0.edges:
    if x not in high_values:
        G1.remove_edge(x[0],x[1])

# Format node sizes: 

# get the inward degree for each node and store them as a list of (node_number, degree)
in_deg = G1.in_degree()
# Multiply the node degree to 1000 as the node size 
in_deg = [int(in_deg[node])*500 for node in G1.nodes()]


# Format weights: 

weights = []
for edge, weight in nx.get_edge_attributes(G1,'weight').items():
    weights.append(weight)

#weighted_egdes = [(0.1+abs(weight))**20 for weight in weights]
weighted_egdes = [(0.2+abs(weight))**10 for weight in weights]


nx.draw_networkx_nodes(G1, pos, node_size=in_deg,  cmap="spring", alpha=0.7,node_color="orange")
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G1, pos, edge_list = G1.edges, width = weighted_egdes, style = 'solid', edge_color = 'black')
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G1,pos,font_size=11)
plt.show(G1)

Community detection¶

We would like to identify clusters of products that are similar to each other. Let's run the Louvain community detection algorithm to identify clusters:

In [4]:
G3 = nx.read_edgelist("./" + "product_proximity.txt", nodetype=int, data=(('weight',float),), create_using=nx.Graph()  )
In [5]:
product_louvain = community_louvain.best_partition(G3)
community.modularity(product_louvain, G3)

We see that the best partition has a modularity of 0.4 roughly. Below are the values assigned to each node/product:

Name: category predicted, dtype: int64

With community detection algorithms such as Louvain, we observe that the accuracy on category 1 (oil and petroleum products) is high unlike for category 7 (labor intensive products) where we see that the there are many different categories predicted. We could assume that it is harder for an algorithmm to predict the category of labor intensive products as it is a really vast and large product category. By running the Louvain algorithm, we observe that it returns 3 different communities for the labor-intensive category, which is strenghtening the point we just made that the labor-intensive category should have many diverse clusters within itself.
